mod.rs
     1‚Üí//! Structured logging.
     2‚Üí//!
     3‚Üí//! Add the `kv` feature to your `Cargo.toml` to enable
     4‚Üí//! this module:
     5‚Üí//!
     6‚Üí//! ```toml
     7‚Üí//! [dependencies.log]
     8‚Üí//! features = ["kv"]
     9‚Üí//! ```
    10‚Üí//!
    11‚Üí//! # Structured logging in `log`
    12‚Üí//!
    13‚Üí//! Structured logging enhances traditional text-based log records with user-defined
    14‚Üí//! attributes. Structured logs can be analyzed using a variety of data processing
    15‚Üí//! techniques, without needing to find and parse attributes from unstructured text first.
    16‚Üí//!
    17‚Üí//! In `log`, user-defined attributes are part of a [`Source`] on the log record.
    18‚Üí//! Each attribute is a key-value; a pair of [`Key`] and [`Value`]. Keys are strings
    19‚Üí//! and values are a datum of any type that can be formatted or serialized. Simple types
    20‚Üí//! like strings, booleans, and numbers are supported, as well as arbitrarily complex
    21‚Üí//! structures involving nested objects and sequences.
    22‚Üí//!
    23‚Üí//! ## Adding key-values to log records
    24‚Üí//!
    25‚Üí//! Key-values appear before the message format in the `log!` macros:
    26‚Üí//!
    27‚Üí//! ```
    28‚Üí//! # use log::info;
    29‚Üí//! info!(a = 1; "Something of interest");
    30‚Üí//! ```
    31‚Üí//!
    32‚Üí//! Key-values support the same shorthand identifier syntax as `format_args`:
    33‚Üí//!
    34‚Üí//! ```
    35‚Üí//! # use log::info;
    36‚Üí//! let a = 1;
    37‚Üí//!
    38‚Üí//! info!(a; "Something of interest");
    39‚Üí//! ```
    40‚Üí//!
